\section{Background}
Most of the early studies focusing on the syllable in language processing involved French and English monolingual speakers \parencite{Mehler1981-vi, Cutler1986-zl}. Then, in the early 90s, bilingual French--English speakers were studied under the same paradigm \parencite{Cutler1992-qq}. Finally, around the same time, Spanish speakers were studied for the first time \parencite{Sebastian-Galles1992-xd, Bradley1993-qq}. These previous findings reported most of their findings in terms of whether or not a crossover effect was found or not. Understanding what is meant by the crossover effect is paramount to understanding the results found in previous literature and interpreting the results of the current study. In previous literature, researchers analyzed the data according to (2) x (2) anova where the target syllable structure, the syllable for which participants monitored, was the first factor and contained two levels---CV and CVC. The second factor was the word-initial syllable of the presented word where the participant could find the target syllable for which they were monitoring. Similarly, the second factor---word-initial syllable---had two levels which were also CV and CVC structures. The crossover effect was considered the result of favorable conditions that produced faster reaction times for matching conditions. For example, if a syllabic segmentation strategy is being used, then monitoring for a CV syllable string should be detected faster when the presented word has a CV word-initial syllable when compared to a presented word that has a CVC word-initial syllable. Likewise, monitoring for a CVC syllable structure should be found faster when the word containing the target begins with a CVC word-initial syllable rather than a CV one. In other words, monitoring for a syllable structure that matches the initial syllable structure of the word containing it makes it an easier task. The easier task is marked by the faster reaction times needed to indicate the syllable had been detected. The results of statistical analysis indicated the crossover effect was present with a significant interaction between the search target structure and the initial syllable structure of the presented word containing the target. 

