As in previous studies on syllable monitoring, monolingual English speakers were tasked with monitoring for CV and CVC syllables in the English materials. Again, Bradley et al. \parencite*{Bradley1993-qq} presented the targets auditorily and ran a different group recruited from the same speaker population to show that this difference did not cause the effects in their results as compared to those found by Cutler et al. \parencite*{Cutler1986-zl}. \ttodo{This arguement or sentence is unclear} In contrast to the Spanish monitoring in experiment 1, but not unlike the English montioring by Cutler et al. \parencite*{Cutler1986-zl}, there was no crossover effect found with the English speakers monitoring English words. Continuing in the vein of replicating the French and English findings of Cutler et al. \parencite*{Cutler1986-zl}, Bradley et al. \parencite*{Bradley1993-qq} tested native Spanish speakers with the English material they had created. Similar to the naive monitoring of Spanish, a procedural change included showing the English target to monolingual Spanish speakers in addition to the auditory presentation. The results revealed no crossover effect as evidenced by the absence of interaction between target structure and word-initial syllable structure with the English data being monitored by Spanish speakers. This finding was interesting because French and Spanish are both romance languages, are both considered to be syllable timed and neither have ambisyllabicity. However, the transference of a syllabic segemenation strategy from French to English in Cutler et al. \parencite*{Cutler1986-zl} does not seem to hold true for Spanish speakers.

